text=(:if [ authgroup @tas || authgroup @admins || equal {$Author} '' ]:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=edit|Edit this page]] \\%0aStatus: {GradebookArticles.{$Name}$:Status} %0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!{$:Category}]]%0a%0a!Aymara Tribe and the Aymara language%0a%0a:Author: allenzheng%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aAn article on the Aymara language, one of the larger native languages spoken historically in the Inca Empire and in modern day Bolivia and Peru%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aI chose Aymara because I've been interested in Inca civilization and their unique approach to many, now well established norms such as a non-market economy or lack of written language. The indigenous people of the Andes region of South America are referred to as the Aymara or Aimara tribe. The people of the region have been under the rule of many different empires, the Spanish in the 16th century and even the Inca in the 15th century. Despite this, the language remains popular and is even the official language of Bolivia and Peru and a recognized language in Chile. Similar to many South American languages, the people speaker are not purely indigenous. There are more than a million native speakers, used in daily life with many resources to learn. There is a comprehensive dictionary and many apps to give information on the text. There is a large community around learning the language, though many resources are in Spanish as the region mainly speaks Spanish. https://youtu.be/FvGw76kHQGE https://www.katari.org/diccionario/diccionario.php%0a%0aNon native sources like Wikipedia give a more scientific examination of the language, such as details on the similarities with Quecha and possible, though unlikely historical ties. They also present many more details on the phonology orthography, approaching the subject as an object of study. Though this is shared with other mainstream languages. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aymara_language%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:elseif [ equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:andrewid} '' || equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:section} '' ] :)%0a%0aYou must enter your andrew ID and section before submitting an expansion. %0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a%0a----%0a(:if equal {$Author} {$:Author}:)%0a!!Change article category%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#changearticlecategory:)%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a%0a(:Section: F:)%0a(:Category: IndigenousLanguagesOfTheAmericas:)%0a(:Title: Aymara Tribe and the Aymara language:)
